  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and in the communities I've worked with over the years. Growing up in Italy, I was taught that success in technical fields was for the 'strong-willed' and 'lucky' few, not for people like me who didn't have the same advantages. My parents, both university graduates, tried to encourage me to pursue a career in engineering, but I found myself more drawn to the creative side of things. Today, as a self-employed hairdresser in Milan, I've noticed how the same stereotypes that once held back my own ambitions can hold back others too. When I talk to young women and minorities in the city, they often feel like they don't belong in STEM because of what they've been told about their abilities. This isn't just about individual confidence—it's a systemic issue that affects everyone who feels they're not 'meant' for a particular field. Should we address it? Absolutely. But the way we do it matters. In my experience, the most effective approach is to create spaces where people feel safe to make mistakes without judgment. For example, when I run workshops for kids in my community, I focus on hands-on projects that let them explore their interests without the pressure of 'being right.' It's about building trust, not just fixing problems. The key is to listen first and understand the root of the problem before jumping to solutions. I've seen how a single conversation can change someone's perspective, especially when it's grounded in empathy and shared experiences. In the end, addressing stereotype threat in STEM isn't about changing the system overnight—it's about creating a culture where everyone feels they belong, no matter their background.",
